issue.title: Constructor Difference for SignigingCredentails in .NET Core
issue.body:
I am working on migrating my app from .NET Core to .NET Framework.

In the codebase, we have following piece of code -

```
                samlAssertion.SigningCredentials = new SigningCredentials(
                    securityKey,
                    SecurityAlgorithms.RsaSha1Signature,
                    SecurityAlgorithms.Sha1Digest,
                    securityKeyIdentifier);
```

In the .NET Core implementation, I see that the `SigningCredentials` class inside `Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens.Saml` namespace **does not** takes `securityKeyIdentifier`.

I looked at the .NET Framework implementation and could see that securityKeyIdentifier was just present as a public field with a getter and was not used in any computation logic inside `SigningCredentails`.

So, it looks like it is not needed, but it would be great if anyone can confirm that we are good using the .NET Core constructor without `securityKeyIdentifier`.

issue.title: Constructor difference for SamlSubject and SamlAttribute in .NET Core
issue.body:
Hi,

I am working on migrating an app from .NET Framework to .NET Core. I see some functionality missing in `SamlSubject` and `SamlAttribute` in .NET Core. Sharing details below -

### Scenario - 1

The constructor for `SamlSubject` in .NET Framework is -

```
public SamlSubject(
                        string nameFormat,
			string nameQualifier, 
			string name, 
			IEnumerable<string> confirmations, 
			string confirmationData, 
			SecurityKeyIdentifier securityKeyIdentifier)
```

In .NET Framework, the constructor available to us is -

```
        public SamlSubject(
            string nameFormat,
            string nameQualifier,
            string name,
            IEnumerable<string> confirmations,
            string confirmationData)
```

`SecurityKeyIdentifier` was used by our .NET Framework implementation. Currently, I do not see a way to use this with .NET Core. 

**Q - What is the recommended way to proceed for the above?**

----

### Scenario 2 -

In .NET Framework version of out app, we have the following code -

```
            SamlAttributeStatement samlAttributeStatement = new SamlAttributeStatement(
                subject,
                new[] 
                {
                    new SamlAttribute(new Claim(XmlConstants.TargetTenantClaimType, targetTenant, Rights.PossessProperty)), 
                    new SamlAttribute(new Claim(XmlConstants.LinkedPartnerOrganizationIdClaimType, this.ExternalOrganizationId, Rights.PossessProperty)), 
                    new SamlAttribute(XmlConstants.XmlNamespace, XmlConstants.LinkedPartnerGroupId, this.RoleGroupExternalObjectIds), 
                });

```

Here, we see that we have a way to instantiate `SamlAttribute` using `Claim`. In the .NET Framework, I see no constructor for `SamlAttribute` which takes Claim as an argument.

The new constructor takes 3 arguments -

1. Namespace
2. Name
3. Value

**Q - I wanted to check what is the correct way to port the .NET Framework? Is it fine if we just supply the above 3 values? Will the functionality be uniform?**

The above code would look like -

```
            SamlAttributeStatement samlAttributeStatement = new SamlAttributeStatement(
                subject,
                new[]
                {
                    new SamlAttribute(XmlConstants.XmlNamespace, XmlConstants.TargetTenant, targetTenant),
                    new SamlAttribute(XmlConstants.XmlNamespace, XmlConstants.LinkedPartnerOrganizationId, this.ExternalOrganizationId),
                    new SamlAttribute(XmlConstants.XmlNamespace, XmlConstants.LinkedPartnerGroupId, this.RoleGroupExternalObjectIds),
                });
```

issue.title: Equivalent of SamlConstants.HolderOfKey not present in NetCore
issue.body:
We are working on migrating our app from .NET Framework to .NET Core. In our app, certain flow uses SAML related code.

A snippet from the code is -

```
            SamlSubject subject = new SamlSubject(
                UpnUri,
                null, /* nameQualifier  */
                this.UPN, /* name */
                new string[] { SamlConstants.HolderOfKey }, /* confirmations */
                null, /* confirmationData  */
                proofKeyIdentifier /* securityKeyIdentifier */);
```

As seen from the above implementation, the `SamlSubject` (present in `namespace System.IdentityModel.Tokens` for .NET Framework) uses `SamlConstants.HolderOfKey`.

When moving to .NET Core, we found that the `SamlConstants` (present in `namespace Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens.Saml`) does **not** contains the constant for `HolderOfKey`.

We found that something similar is present in `Saml2` namespace as -

`Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens.Saml2.Saml2Constants.ConfirmationMethods.HolderOfKeyString`.

We wanted to check if we can use this string from `Saml2` inside `SamlSubject`? If not, what is the right way to get this constant for SamlSubject?

issue.title: [Feature Request] Use GeneratedRegex in JwtTokenUtilities

labels.name: Enhancement
labels.description: The issue is a new feature

labels.name: Customer reported
labels.description: Indicates issue was opened by customer

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
When publishing an app for NativeAOT (see #2035), IL generation at runtime is disabled.

One usage of IL generation at runtime is `new Regex(regex, RegexOptions.Compiled)`. At startup, RegexOptions.Compiled instructs the Regex engine to generate IL given the regular expression, and use the generated IL, instead of interpreting the expression every time it is executed.

When you use a "Compiled" Regex in NativeAOT, the Regex engine ignores the `Compiled` option and instead falls back to interpreting the expression at runtime. This means your app runs slower when on NativeAOT.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
The solution to this issue is to use the new Regex Source Generator:

* https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/base-types/regular-expression-source-generators
* https://devblogs.microsoft.com/dotnet/regular-expression-improvements-in-dotnet-7/#source-generation

However, this feature is only available when targeting `net7.0` and above. So we would need the following:

1. We would need to target `net7.0` in `Microsoft.IdentityModel.JsonWebTokens.csproj`.
    - This means updating any CI scripts and build machines to use the .NET 7 SDK.
2. JwtTokenUtilities would look like this:

```C#
    public partial class JwtTokenUtilities
    {
        private const int RegexMatchTimeoutMilliseconds = 100;
        /// <summary>
        /// Regex that is used to figure out if a token is in JWS format.
        /// </summary>
        public static Regex RegexJws = CreateJwsRegex();

        /// <summary>
        /// Regex that is used to figure out if a token is in JWE format.
        /// </summary>
        public static Regex RegexJwe = CreateJweRegex();

#if NET7_0_OR_GREATER
        [GeneratedRegex(JwtConstants.JsonCompactSerializationRegex, RegexOptions.CultureInvariant, RegexMatchTimeoutMilliseconds)]
        private static partial Regex CreateJwsRegex();
        [GeneratedRegex(JwtConstants.JweCompactSerializationRegex, RegexOptions.CultureInvariant, RegexMatchTimeoutMilliseconds)]
        private static partial Regex CreateJweRegex();
#else
        private static Regex CreateJwsRegex() => new Regex(JwtConstants.JsonCompactSerializationRegex, RegexOptions.Compiled | RegexOptions.CultureInvariant, TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(RegexMatchTimeoutMilliseconds));
        private static Regex CreateJweRegex() => new Regex(JwtConstants.JweCompactSerializationRegex, RegexOptions.Compiled | RegexOptions.CultureInvariant, TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(RegexMatchTimeoutMilliseconds));
#endif
```

Note that there are benefits to using the source generator even when not in NativeAOT mode. For example, your app starts faster because it doesn't need to generate IL at runtime.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Live with slower NativeAOT applications.

**Additional context**
The following benchmark shows `JsonWebTokenHandler.CanReadToken` performance is 2-3x faster on NativeAOT when using the source generated Regex:

```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
    <TargetFramework>net7.0</TargetFramework>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <ProjectReference Include="\git\azure-activedirectory-identitymodel-extensions-for-dotnet\src\Microsoft.IdentityModel.JsonWebTokens\Microsoft.IdentityModel.JsonWebTokens.csproj" />
    <PackageReference Include="BenchmarkDotNet" Version="0.13.5" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
```

```C#
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Configs;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Jobs;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;
using Microsoft.IdentityModel.JsonWebTokens;
using Perfolizer.Horology;

var job = Job.Default
                    .WithWarmupCount(1) // 1 warmup is enough for our purpose
                    .WithIterationTime(TimeInterval.FromMilliseconds(250)) // the default is 0.5s per iteration, which is slighlty too much for us
                    .WithMinIterationCount(15)
                    .WithMaxIterationCount(20) // we don't want to run more that 20 iterations
                    .DontEnforcePowerPlan(); // make sure BDN does not try to enforce High Performance power plan on Windows

var config = DefaultConfig.Instance
    .AddJob(job.AsDefault()); // tell BDN that this are our default settings

BenchmarkSwitcher
    .FromAssembly(typeof(Program).Assembly)
    .Run(args, config);


public class JsonWebTokenHandlerBenchmark
{
    const string jwsToken = "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..Ol6TuW6OgkaLcuFWx5O4JGcGwqdG9IlvA84roUQPhc8";
    const string jweToken = "eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6IlJzYVNlY3VyaXR5S2V5XzIwNDgiLCJ0eXAiOiJKV1QifQ.eyJlbWFpbCI6IkJvYkBjb250b3NvLmNvbSIsImdpdmVuX25hbWUiOiJCb2IiLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwOi8vRGVmYXVsdC5Jc3N1ZXIuY29tIiwiYXVkIjoiaHR0cDovL0RlZmF1bHQuQXVkaWVuY2UuY29tIiwibmJmIjoiMTQ4OTc3NTYxNyIsImV4cCI6IjE2MTYwMDYwMTcifQ.GcIi6FGp1JS5VF70_ULa8g6GTRos9Y7rUZvPAo4hm10bBNfGhdd5uXgsJspiQzS8vwJQyPlq8a_BpL9TVKQyFIRQMnoZWe90htmNWszNYbd7zbLJZ9AuiDqDzqzomEmgcfkIrJ0VfbER57U46XPnUZQNng2XgMXrXmIKUqEph_vLGXYRQ4ndfwtRrR6BxQFd1PS1T5KpEoUTusI4VEsMcutzfXUygLDiRKIcnLFA0kQpeoHllO4Nb_Sxv63GCb0d1076FfSEYtyRxF4YSCz1In-ee5dwEK8Mw3nHscu-1hn0Fe98RBs-4OrUzI0WcV8mq9IIB3i-U-CqCJEP_hVCiA";

    private readonly JsonWebTokenHandler handler = new JsonWebTokenHandler();

    [Benchmark]
    public bool JWS() => handler.CanReadToken(jwsToken);

    [Benchmark]
    public bool JWE() => handler.CanReadToken(jweToken);
}
```

### Existing Code Normal CoreCLR (not AOT'd)
`dotnet run -c Release -f net7.0`

| Method |     Mean |    Error |  StdDev |
|------- |---------:|---------:|--------:|
|    JWS | 662.5 ns | 10.21 ns | 9.05 ns |
|    JWE | 861.8 ns |  5.27 ns | 4.12 ns |

### Existing Code Publish AOT
`dotnet run -c Release -f net7.0 --runtimes nativeaot7.0`

| Method |     Mean |     Error |    StdDev |
|------- |---------:|----------:|----------:|
|    JWS | 1.798 us | 0.0222 us | 0.0197 us |
|    JWE | 2.376 us | 0.0106 us | 0.0099 us |

* Note the change in time units from nanoseconds to microseconds.

### Proposed Code Normal CoreCLR (not AOT'd)
`dotnet run -c Release -f net7.0`

| Method |     Mean |    Error |   StdDev |
|------- |---------:|---------:|---------:|
|    JWS | 598.0 ns |  6.53 ns |  6.11 ns |
|    JWE | 788.3 ns | 11.16 ns | 10.44 ns |

### Proposed Code Publish AOT
`dotnet run -c Release -f net7.0 --runtimes nativeaot7.0`

| Method |     Mean |    Error |   StdDev |
|------- |---------:|---------:|---------:|

|    JWE | 702.2 ns |  5.12 ns |  4.54 ns |

pull_request.title: Use source-generated Regex in JwtTokenUtilities
pull_request.body:
Fixes #2036.

I agree with @eerhardt on the fact that the current implementation already uses Regex's, so it's easy to improve it by using source-generated Regex's. If, later, we want to further improve performance by changing the implementation, we're free to do so.
